### Enums in C#

An enum (enumeration) is a value type that defines a set of named constants.

### Declaring Enums

```csharp
public enum DayOfWeek
{
    Monday,      // 0
    Tuesday,     // 1
    Wednesday,   // 2
    Thursday,    // 3
    Friday,       // 4
    Saturday,    // 5
    Sunday       // 6
}
```

### Using Enums

```csharp
DayOfWeek today = DayOfWeek.Monday;

if (today == DayOfWeek.Saturday || today == DayOfWeek.Sunday)
    Console.WriteLine("Weekend!");
else
    Console.WriteLine("Weekday");
```

### Custom Values

```csharp
public enum HttpStatusCode
{
    OK = 200,
    Created = 201,
    BadRequest = 400,
    Unauthorized = 401,
    NotFound = 404,
    InternalServerError = 500
}
```

### Enum as Flags (Bitwise)

```csharp
[Flags]
public enum FilePermissions
{
    None = 0,
    Read = 1,
    Write = 2,
    Execute = 4,
    ReadWrite = Read | Write,
    All = Read | Write | Execute
}

// Usage
FilePermissions perms = FilePermissions.Read | FilePermissions.Write;
bool canRead = perms.HasFlag(FilePermissions.Read);
```

### Enum Methods

```csharp
// Parse string to enum
DayOfWeek day = (DayOfWeek)Enum.Parse(typeof(DayOfWeek), "Monday");

// TryParse (generic)
Enum.TryParse("Tuesday", out DayOfWeek result);

// Get all values
DayOfWeek[] allDays = (DayOfWeek[])Enum.GetValues(typeof(DayOfWeek));

// Get name from value
string name = Enum.GetName(typeof(DayOfWeek), 1);  // "Tuesday"

// Get numeric value
int value = (int)DayOfWeek.Wednesday;  // 2
```

### Enum Underlying Types

```csharp
public enum Color : byte  // Default is int
{
    Red = 0,
    Green = 1,
    Blue = 2
}

// Allowed: byte, sbyte, short, ushort, int, uint, long, ulong
```

### Enum as Switch

```csharp
switch (status)
{
    case HttpStatusCode.OK:
        Console.WriteLine("Success");
        break;
    case HttpStatusCode.NotFound:
        Console.WriteLine("Not found");
        break;
    default:
        Console.WriteLine($"Status code: {(int)status}");
        break;
}
```

> **Key Point:** Enums improve code readability by using meaningful names instead of magic numbers. Use the `[Flags]` attribute for bitmask enums. Enum values are integers by default but can be any integer type. Use `Enum.TryParse()` for safe string-to-enum conversion.

### Best Practices

| Practice | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| Singular names | `DayOfWeek` not `DaysOfWeek` |
| Flags attribute | Required for bitwise operations |
| Default value 0 | Should represent "None" or "Unknown" |
| Explicit values | Helps with serialization stability |
| Avoid complex logic | Enums are for simple constants |

